Contrary to Nietzsche’s famous proclamation that “God is dead,” God and religion are, for better or worse, pervasive aspects of our society.
Regarding the development of our understanding of the divine, Aslan asks,Is God the animating force that connects all living beings, as our prehistoric ancestors seem to believe?
They worshiped one god, a god they believed to be the high god of the universe, but still believed in the existence of other gods.
God IS everything that exists” and that “God did not make us in his image; nor did we simply make God in ours.
Rather, we are the image of God in the world – not in form or likeness, but in essence…The world is God’s self-expression.